3 One Parameter Model: Binary Treatment Variable

3.1 Mimicking Potential Outcomes

To compute the mimicked potential outcome: \(H_{s,k}(t)\) for \(k \in \{7-2019, \dotsc, 7-2000 \}\) and \(t < k\), we first extract \(Y_{s,k}\). We then compute \(\gamma_t^k = exp(\psi*(a_{s,t} - a_{s,t-1}))\). Let \(t_s^*\) be the treatment time interval for state \(s\). We focus on data points for which \(t \leq t_s^*\) and \(t<k\). This is because for the treatment initiation model, we include data points for which \(t \leq t_s^*\) and we want \(t<k\). We let \(a_{s,t}\) be a binary variable. For these data points we are intersted in, we create the variable hkt which is equal to \(\frac{Y_{s,k}}{exp(\psi)}\) when \(k > t_s^*\) (i.e. \(Y_{s,k}\) is a treated outcome) and equal to \(Y_{s,k}\) when \(k \leq t_s^*\) (i.e. \(Y_{s,k}\) is an untreated outcome). Lastly, we combine all these datapoints together for each \(k\) into a dataset to be returned to use in the treatment initiation model.

compute_mimick_potential_outcome <- function(dataFrame, gamma_k_t_when_treated){
  #new_df is the dataset we will return, with the new rows appended
  #we initialize it first as the input dataset df
  new_data_frame <- data.frame()
  
  #here, k is the time in which we observe the outcome and t is the time of the treatments
  #so we have k > t
  for(k in max(unique(dataFrame$Time_Period_ID)):2){
    #we first pull out the risk of OD at time k, so Y_k
    outcome_k_data <- dataFrame %>%
      arrange(State) %>%
      filter(Time_Period_ID == k) %>%
      dplyr::select(State, prop_dead, Intervention_First_Date, Time_Period_Start)
    
    #compute H_k(t) given gamma_k_t_when_treated:
    #here, let t^* = treatment time 
    #if k <= t^*, then H_k(t) = Y_k since we havent treated yet, so doesn't affect
    #if t^* < t < k, then H_k(t) = Y_k since a_{t} - a_{t-1} = 0
    #if t <= t^* < k, then H_k(t) = Y_k/gamma_k_t_when_treated
    outcome_k_data$hkt <- ifelse(outcome_k_data$Time_Period_Start > outcome_k_data$Intervention_First_Date,
                                 outcome_k_data$prop_dead/gamma_k_t_when_treated, outcome_k_data$prop_dead)
    
    #filter the data for which A_{s,t} = 0 and the time interval that contains the treatment time since we only need these data 
    #to predict treatment initiation for the model
    #we also filter so that the t < k
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data <- dataFrame %>%
      arrange(State, Time_Period_ID) %>%
      #filter for t <= t^* because we use these time periods to predict treatment initiation
      filter(Time_Period_Start <= Intervention_First_Date,
             #filter for t < k
             Time_Period_ID < k)
    
    #merge the filtered dataset with the outcome_k_data which contains the computed H_k(t)
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data <- merge(untreated_and_first_tx_date_data, outcome_k_data[,c("State", "hkt")], by = "State")
    
    #compute values that may be useful
    #compute k - t
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data$k_minus_t <- k - untreated_and_first_tx_date_data$Time_Period_ID
    #compute indicator of whether Y_{s,k} is treated outcome
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data$treated_outcome_indicator <- unique(outcome_k_data$Time_Period_Start) > 
      untreated_and_first_tx_date_data$Intervention_First_Date
    
    #we then append the rows to the new_data_frame
    new_data_frame <- rbind(new_data_frame, untreated_and_first_tx_date_data)
  }
  new_data_frame
}

3.2 Finding \(\psi\): \(\gamma_t^k = exp(\psi (a_t - a_{t-1}))\)

Here, we assume that the treatment effects model is given by the one parameter model: \[\gamma_t^k = exp(\psi*(a_t - a_{t-1})),\] where \(a_t\) and \(a_{t-1}\) are binary variables (for now) indicating whether there have ever been any DIH prosecution media alerts by time \(t\) and \(t-1\). Further, we have \(k > t_s^*\).

We fit a treatment initiation model for the response dih_exposure which is a binary variable indicating whether the state was exposed to DIH prosecution in the media, where we use the following as predictors:

  • sum_policies is the number of other policy measures that have been enacted from time 1 until time \(t-1\)
  • hkt is the computed \(H_k(t)\)
  • Time_Period_ID is the linear time effect.

Recall that the model_data only contains the datapoints for which \(t \leq t^*\). For each value \(\psi\), we extract the coefficient of hkt from the treatment initiation model, and we find the \(\psi\) that leads to a coefficient of zero. We also store a vector of conf_int which stores the values of \(\psi\) if the Wald test for the coefficient of hkt is not statistically significant at the \(alpha = 0.05\) level.

#create a vector of 100 psi
# psi_grid_params <- seq(-0.1012847, -0.1012846, length.out = 100)
psi_grid_params <- seq(-.2, .1, by = 0.001)

#initialize the vector of coefficients for H(t) in treatment initiation model
coef_hkt <- rep(NA, length(psi_grid_params))
conf_int <- c()
for(grid_point in 1:length(psi_grid_params)){
  #statement to print the status of the for loop
  # if(grid_point%%10 == 0){print(grid_point)}
  #compute gamma_k_t given the psi_grid_params[grid_point]. Since here, the treatment is binary, we only need the value for
  #exp(psi_grid_params[grid_point])
  gamma_k_t_when_treated <- exp(psi_grid_params[grid_point])

  #compute H(t) given the dataset and gamma_k_t_when_treated
  model_data <- compute_mimick_potential_outcome(treat_data, gamma_k_t_when_treated)
 
  #fit model for treatment initiation
  treat_model <- glm(dih_exposure~ 
                       sum_policies + 
                       hkt + 
                       Time_Period_ID,
                     data = model_data, family = "binomial")
  
  #store the coefficient for H_k(t)
  coef_hkt[grid_point] <- coef(treat_model)["hkt"]
  
  #conduct the Wald Test for the third coefficient, which is H_k(t) here since the first coefficient is the intercept
  store_wald_test <- wald.test(vcov(treat_model), coef(treat_model), 3)
  #we then store the p-value and store the psi values if the p-value > 0.05
  pval <- store_wald_test$result$chi2["P"]
  if(pval > 0.05){
    conf_int <- rbind(conf_int, psi_grid_params[grid_point])
  }
}

3.3 Checking Grid-Search

Since we can compute the \(\psi\) in a one-parameter model from the unbiased estimating equation, we do so to check the grid-search value. We showed that \[E\left(\sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = k-1}^{T} \vec{q}{_t}^{k}(\bar{X}_{s,t}, \bar{A}_{s,t-1}) H_{s,k}(t) \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}({g(A}_{s,t}) - \lambda_{s,t})\right) = 0.\] We let \(\vec{q}{_t}^{k}(\bar{X}_{s,t}, \bar{A}_{s,t-1}) = 1\) and \(H_{s,k}(t) = \frac{Y_{s,k}}{exp(\psi)} \mathbb{I}\{k > t_s^*\} + Y_{s,k} \mathbb{I}\{k \leq t_s^*\}\) where \(t_s^*\) is the treatment time for state \(s\). Furthermore, we let \(g(A_{s,t}) = \mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\}\) and \(\lambda_{s,t} = p_{s,t}\), the probability of treatment. Then, we have the following: \[\begin{align*} 0 &= \sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = 0}^{k-1} \left(\frac{Y_{s,k}}{exp(\psi)} \mathbb{I}\{k > t_s^*\} + Y_{s,k} \mathbb{I}\{k \leq t_s^*\}\right) \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}(\mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\} - p_{s,t}) \\ &= \sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = 0}^{k-1} Y_{s,k}exp(-\psi) \mathbb{I}\{k > t_s^*\} \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}(\mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\} - p_{s,t}) \\ &+ \sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = 0}^{k-1} Y_{s,k} \mathbb{I}\{k \leq t_s^*\} \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}(\mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\} - p_{s,t}) \\ &\Rightarrow exp(-\psi) \sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = 0}^{k-1} Y_{s,k} \mathbb{I}\{k > t_s^*\} \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}(\mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\} - p_{s,t}) = -\sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = 0}^{k-1} Y_{s,k} \mathbb{I}\{k \leq t_s^*\} \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}(\mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\} - p_{s,t}) \\ &\Rightarrow exp(-\psi) = -\frac{\sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = 0}^{k-1} Y_{s,k} \mathbb{I}\{k \leq t_s^*\} \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}(\mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\} - p_{s,t})}{\sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = 0}^{k-1} Y_{s,k} \mathbb{I}\{k > t_s^*\} \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}(\mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\} - p_{s,t})} \\ &\Rightarrow \psi = - log\left(-\frac{\sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = 0}^{k-1} Y_{s,k} \mathbb{I}\{k \leq t_s^*\} \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}(\mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\} - p_{s,t})}{\sum_s \sum_{k=1}^{T + 1} \sum_{t = 0}^{k-1} Y_{s,k} \mathbb{I}\{k > t_s^*\} \mathbb{I}\{\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\}(\mathbb{I}\{A_{s,t} > 0\} - p_{s,t})}\right), \end{align*}\]

where we model \(p_{s,t}\) using the sum_policies and Time_Period_ID for data points in which \(\bar{A}_{s,t-1} = \bar{0}\). However, if the fraction is positive, then we arrive at an issue since we cannot take the log of a negative.

#filter the data to fit the treatment initiation model
treatment_initiation_data <- treat_data %>%
  # filter data so that t < t_s^* + 1
  filter(Intervention_Redefined < 1)

#fit the treatment initiation model

4 Two Parameter Model: Binary Treatment

4.1 Mimicking Potential Outcomes

To compute the mimicked potential outcome: \(H_{s,k}(t)\) for \(k \in \{7-2019, \dotsc, 7-2000 \}\) and \(t < k\), we first extract \(Y_{s,k}\). We then compute \(\gamma_t^k = exp(\psi_1*(a_t - a_{t-1}) + \psi_2*(a_t - a_{t-1})*(k-t_s^*))\). Let \(t_s^*\) be the treatment time interval for state \(s\). We focus on data points for which \(t \leq t_s^*\) and \(t<k\). This is because for the treatment initiation model, we include data points for which \(t \leq t_s^*\) and we want \(t<k\). We let \(a_{s,t}\) be a binary variable. For these data points we are interested in, we create the variable hkt which is equal to \(\frac{Y_{s,k}}{exp(\psi_1 + \psi_2(k-t_s^*))}\) when \(k > t_s^*\) (i.e. \(Y_{s,k}\) is a treated outcome) and equal to \(Y_{s,k}\) when \(k \leq t_s^*\) (i.e. \(Y_{s,k}\) is an untreated outcome). Lastly, we combine all these datapoints together for each \(k\) into a dataset to be returned to use in the treatment initiation model.

compute_mimick_potential_outcome_two_parameter_model <- function(dataFrame, psi_1, psi_2){
  #new_df is the dataset we will return, with the new rows appended
  #we initialize it first as the input dataset df
  new_data_frame <- data.frame()
  
  #here, k is the time in which we observe the outcome and t is the time of the treatments
  #so we have k > t
  for(k in max(unique(dataFrame$Time_Period_ID)):2){
    #we first pull out the risk of OD at time k, so Y_k
    outcome_k_data <- dataFrame %>%
      arrange(State) %>%
      filter(Time_Period_ID == k) %>%
      dplyr::select(State, prop_dead, Intervention_First_Date, Time_Period_Start)
    
    #pull the treatment time period for the first treatment date
    tx_time_period_data <- dataFrame %>%
      filter(Time_Period_Start == floor_date(Intervention_First_Date, "6 months")) %>%
      select(State, Time_Period_ID)
    
    #rename the Time_Period_ID
    colnames(tx_time_period_data) <- c("State", "tx_time_period")
    
    #merge it with outcome_k_data
    #we keep all rows in outcome_k_data since Hawaii doesn't have a treatment time
    outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period <- merge(outcome_k_data, tx_time_period_data, by = "State",
                                             all.x = TRUE)
    
    #compute gamma_k_t_when_treated but without the exp(psi_2*(k-t)) part since we don't know what k-t is yet
    #we multiply exp(psi_2*(k-t)) to the gamma_k_t_when_treated in line 295
    gamma_k_t_when_treated_only_psi_1 <- exp(psi_1)
    
    #compute H_k(t) given gamma_k_t_when_treated:
    #here, let t^* = treatment time 
    #if k <= t^*, then H_k(t) = Y_k since we havent treated yet, so doesn't affect
    #if t^* < t < k, then H_k(t) = Y_k since a_{t} - a_{t-1} = 0
    #if t <= t^* < k, then H_k(t) = Y_k/gamma_k_t_when_treated
    outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period$hkt <- ifelse(outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period$Time_Period_Start >
                                   outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period$Intervention_First_Date,
                                 outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period$prop_dead/
                                   (gamma_k_t_when_treated_only_psi_1*
                                      exp(psi_2*(k - outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period$tx_time_period))), 
                                 outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period$prop_dead)
    
    #compute k - t_s^*
    outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period$k_minus_t_s <- k - outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period$tx_time_period
    
    #filter the data for which A_{s,t} = 0 and the time interval that contains the treatment time since we only need these data 
    #to predict treatment initiation for the model
    #we also filter so that the t < k
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data <- dataFrame %>%
      arrange(State, Time_Period_ID) %>%
      #filter for t <= t^* because we use these time periods to predict treatment initiation
      filter(Time_Period_Start <= Intervention_First_Date,
             #filter for t < k
             Time_Period_ID < k)
    
    #merge the filtered dataset with the outcome_k_data which contains the computed H_k(t)
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data <- merge(untreated_and_first_tx_date_data, 
                                              outcome_k_data_w_tx_time_period[,c("State", "hkt", "k_minus_t_s")], by = "State")
    
    #compute k - t
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data$k_minus_t <- k - untreated_and_first_tx_date_data$Time_Period_ID
    
    #we then append the rows to the new_data_frame
    new_data_frame <- rbind(new_data_frame, untreated_and_first_tx_date_data)
  }
  new_data_frame
}

4.2 Finding \(\psi = (\psi_1, \psi_2)\): \(\gamma_t^k = exp(\psi_1 (a_t - a_{t-1}) + \psi_2(a_t - a_{t-1})(k - t_s^*))\)

Here, we assume that the treatment effects model is given by the two parameter model: \[\gamma_t^k = exp(\psi_1*(a_t - a_{t-1}) + \psi_2 *(a_t - a_{t-1})*(k-t_s^*)),\] where \(a_t\) and \(a_{t-1}\) are binary variables (for now) indicating whether there have ever been any DIH prosecution media alerts by time \(t\) and \(t-1\) and \(k - t_s^*\) indicates the length of treatment. Further, we have \(k > t_s^*\).

We fit a treatment initiation model for the response dih_exposure which is a binary variable indicating whether the state was exposed to DIH prosecution in the media, where we use the following as predictors:

  • sum_policies is the number of other policy measures that have been enacted from time 1 until time \(t-1\)
  • hkt is the computed \(H_k(t)\)
  • hkt*sum_policies is the interaction between the \(H_k(t)\) and the number of policy measures that have been enacted from time 1 until time \(t-1\)
  • Time_Period_ID is the linear time effect.

Recall that the model_data only contains the datapoints for which \(t \leq t^*\). For each value \(\psi\), we extract the coefficient of hkt from the treatment initiation model, and we find the \(\psi\) that leads to a coefficient of zero. We also store a vector of conf_int which stores the values of \(\psi\) if the Wald test for the coefficient of hkt is not statistically significant at the \(alpha = 0.05\) level.

#create a vector of 100 psi
psi_grid_params_two_param <- expand.grid(seq(-5, 5, by = .5), seq(-5, 5, by = 1))
# psi_grid_params_two_param <- expand.grid(seq(0, 1, by = .01), seq(-5, 5, by = 1))

                                                 psi_grid_params_two_param[grid_point, 2])

#the function to compute H(t) = H(t+1)/gamma_t, where gamma_t is given by parameters psi
compute_h_k_t <- function(h_k_t_plus_1, gamma_k_t ){
  h_k_t_plus_1/gamma_k_t
}

compute_mimick_potential_outcome <- function(dataFrame, gamma_k_t){
  #new_df is the dataset we will return, with the new rows appended
  #we initialize it first as the input dataset df
  new_data_frame <- data.frame()
  
  #here, k is the time in which we observe the outcome and t is the time of the treatments
  #so we have k > t
  for(k in max(unique(dataFrame$Time_Period_ID)):2){
    #we first pull out the risk of OD at time k, so Y_k
    outcome_k_data <- dataFrame %>%
      arrange(State) %>%
      filter(Time_Period_ID == k) %>%
      dplyr::select(State, prop_dead)
    
    #compute H_k(t) given gamma_k_t:
    #here, let t^* = treatment time 
    #if t > t^*, then H_k(t) = Y_k since a_{t} - a_{t-1} = 0
    #if t <= t^*, then H_k(t) = Y_k/gamma_k_t
    outcome_k_data$hkt <- outcome_k_data$prop_dead/gamma_k_t
    
    # for(t in (k-1):1){
    #   #creating the dataset for time t -- we first only take the rows for time t
    #   t_data_frame <- dataFrame %>%
    #     arrange(State) %>%
    #     filter(Time_Period_ID == t) 
    #   
    #   #Compute H_k(t). Let t^* be the treatment time. 
    #   #If t>t^*, then H_k(t) = Y_k. If t<= t^* then H_k(t) = Y_k/gamma_k_t
    #   t_data_frame$hkt <- ifelse(t_data_frame$Time_Period_Start <= t_data_frame$Intervention_First_Date, outcome_k, outcome_k/gamma_k_t)
    #   
    #   #we then append the rows to the new_df
    #   new_data_frame <- rbind(new_data_frame, t_data_frame)
    # 
    # }
    
    #filter the data for which A_{s,t} = 0 and the time interval that contains the treatment time since we only need these data 
    #to predict treatment initiation for the model
    #we also filter so that the t < k
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data <- dataFrame %>%
      arrange(State, Time_Period_ID) %>%
      filter(Time_Period_Start <= Intervention_First_Date,
             Time_Period_ID < k)
    
    #merge the filtered dataset with the outcome_k_data which contains the computed H_k(t)
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data <- merge(untreated_and_first_tx_date_data, outcome_k_data[,c("State", "hkt")], by = "State")
    
    #compute k - t
    untreated_and_first_tx_date_data$k_minus_t <- k - untreated_and_first_tx_date_data$Time_Period_ID
    
    #we then append the rows to the new_data_frame
    new_data_frame <- rbind(new_data_frame, untreated_and_first_tx_date_data)
  }
  new_data_frame
}

4.3 \(\gamma_t^k = exp(psi_1(a_t - a_{t-1}) + psi_2(a_t - a_{t-1})(k-t^*))\)

Here, we take into account of the period of time the outcome was observed, after treatment. The longer the treatment period, the larger the effect. \(\gamma_t^k = exp(\psi_1(a_t - a_{t-1}) + \psi_2(a_t - a_{t-1})(k-t))\)

#multiple parameter gamma
compute_mimick_po_w_gamma_function<- function(dataFrame, psi_grid_params, gamma_func){
  #new_df is the dataset we will return, with the new rows appended
  #we initialize it first as the input dataset dataFrame
  new_data_frame <- data.frame()
  
  #here, k is the time in which we observe the outcome and t is the time of the treatments
  #so we have k > t
  for(k in max(unique(dataFrame$Time_Period_ID)):2){
    #we first pull out the risk of OD at time k, so Y_k
    outcome_k <- dataFrame %>%
      arrange(State) %>%
      filter(Time_Period_ID == k) %>%
      dplyr::pull(prop_dead)
    
    #store h(k+1) = Y(k+1)
    hkt_plus_1 <- outcome_k
    for(t in (k-1):1){
      #compute gamma_t using function
      gamma_k_t <- gamma_func(dataFrame, k, t, psi_grid_params)
      
      #for each t< k, taking outcome Y_k, and we blip down at each t: H(t) = H(t + 1)/gamma_t
      hkt <- compute_h_k_t(hkt_plus_1, gamma_k_t)
      
      #creating the dataset for time t -- we first only take the rows for time t
      t_data_frame  <- dataFrame %>%
        arrange(State) %>%
        filter(Time_Period_ID == t) 
      #then for those rows, we add the computed H(t) as a column
      t_data_frame$hkt <- hkt
      
      #also compute k - t
      t_data_frame$len_tx <- k - t
      
      #we then append the rows to the new_df
      new_df <- rbind(new_data_frame, t_data_frame )
      
      #store the H(t) to be used to compute H(t-1)
      hkt_plus_1 <- hkt
    }
  }
  new_data_frame 
}

#create a vector of 100 psi
# psi_grid_params <- seq(-0.1012847, -0.1012846, length.out = 100)
psi_grid_params_two_param <- expand.grid(seq(-5, 5, length.out = 20), seq(-0.263, 0.263, by = 0.01))

#gamma function to compute the two parameter model
gamma_two_param <- function(df, k, t, psi_grid_params){
  #extract the treatment allocation
  df_subset_t <- df %>%
    arrange(State, Time_Period_ID) %>%
    filter(Time_Period_ID == t) %>%
    pull(Intervention_Redefined)
  
  if(t > 1){
    df_subset_t_minus_1 <- df %>%
      arrange(State, Time_Period_ID) %>%
      filter(Time_Period_ID == t-1) %>%
      pull(Intervention_Redefined)
  }else{
    df_subset <- df %>%
    arrange(State, Time_Period_ID) %>%
    filter(Time_Period_ID == t)
    
    df_subset_t_minus_1 <- rep(0, length(df_subset_t))
    df_subset_t_minus_1[df_subset$State == "Ohio"] <- df_subset$Intervention_Redefined[df_subset$State == "Ohio" &
                                                                                         df_subset$Time_Period_ID == t]
    df_subset_t_minus_1[df_subset$State == "Georgia"] <- df_subset$Intervention_Redefined[df_subset$State == "Georgia" &
                                                                                         df_subset$Time_Period_ID == t]
  }

  
  exp(unlist(psi_grid_params[1])*(df_subset_t - df_subset_t_minus_1) + 
        unlist(psi_grid_params[2])*(df_subset_t - df_subset_t_minus_1)*(k-t))
}



#initialize the vector of coefficients for H(t) in treatment initiation model
coef_ht_1 <- coef_ht_2 <- rep(NA, nrow(psi_grid_params_two_param))
for(grid_point in 1:nrow(psi_grid_params_two_param)){
  #statement to print the status of the for loop
  if(grid_point%%10 == 0){print(grid_point)}
  
  #compute H(t) given the dataset and gamma_t
  data_w_ht <- compute_mimick_po_w_gamma_function(treat_data, psi_grid_params_two_param[grid_point,], gamma_two_param)
 
  #filter the dataset to only time periods when treatment hasn't occurred yet and the first time point in which treatment occurred
  model_data <- data_w_ht %>%
    filter(Time_Period_Start <= floor_date(Intervention_First_Date, "6 months"))
  
  #fit model for treatment initiation
  treat_model <- glm(Intervention_Redefined~ 
                       sum_policies + 
                       ht + 
                       Time_Period_ID + 
                       ht*sum_policies,
                     data = model_data, family = "binomial")
  
  #store the coefficient for
  coef_ht_1[grid_point] <- coef(treat_model)["ht"]
  coef_ht_2[grid_point] <- coef(treat_model)["sum_policies:ht"]
  
  
}
